<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Toggling_between_Cameras">Toggling between Cameras</span></h2>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Overview">Overview</span></h3>
<p>In this tutorial I will be showing you how to set up a camera in your scene to be set as your active viewport triggered by a volume within the level blueprint. This will allow you to toggle between the default player camera and the camera you have established.
</p><p>There are some really cool things you can do with this after switching to the camera, like hiding certain actors or adding visual effects.
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Steps_to_Follow">Steps to Follow</span></h3>
<p>Follow these steps in order to get the desired results.
</p><p>1. Create a new project or open an existing one using the ThirdPerson_BP Template.
</p>
<pre>    a. You do not have to use the third person, but because this is what the example is showing, it is just a suggestion.
    b. I did not test this function on the FirstPerson_BP, but it should still function the same.
</pre>
<p>2. Take a static mesh, like the editor cube I used, and pull it into your scene.
</p><p>3. Now create a “Trigger Volume” which will active your “Event” to switch between your current camera and the one you will put in your scene.
</p><p>4. Now create the camera and position it how you would like to be viewed.
</p><p>5. Open your “Level Blueprint” and create an “OnActorBeginOverlap” of your “TriggerBox.”
</p><p>6. Now create a “Set View Target with Blend” node.
</p>
<pre>    a. This node activates your view target.
    b. Allows for multiple blending options when switching for extra customization.
    c. Allows for a time blend in seconds moving from current camera to target camera.
</pre>
<p>7. Add a “Get Player Controller” node and connect that to the “Target” input of the “Set View target with Blend.”
</p>
<pre>    a. Set the Blend time to whatever you would like.
    b. Set the Blend Func (VTBlend Linear) to have smooth linear transition.
</pre>
<p>8. For the “New View Target” create a “CameraActor” reference and connect those together.
</p><p>9. I also added a “Delay” node equal to the length of the Blend Time which hides the actor as soon as the blend is complete.
</p><p>10. When using the "Set Actor Hidden in Game" function, be sure to check or uncheck the "New Hidden" pin to make it visible or invisible.
</p><p>11. Use the images as a reference example to set up the camera switch when entering the “Trigger Volume,” as well as switching back to your regular camera when exiting the volume.
</p><p><br />
</p>
<h3><span class="mw-headline" id="Reference_Images">Reference Images</span></h3>
